<!-- Q16 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Nullity - Unique Solution Condition</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The system \(Ax=b\) has a unique solution for every \(b\in\mathbb{R}^m\) if and only if (with \(A\) being \(m\times n\)):</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(A\) is square (\(m=n\)) and invertible</strong></p><p>Unique solution for every \(b\): need \(T\) bijective \(\Rightarrow m=n\) and \(\det(A)\neq0\). If \(m\neq n\): either underdetermined (\(n>m\): infinitely many solutions when consistent) or overdetermined (\(n<m\): generally no solution). Unique solution for every \(b\Leftrightarrow A\) is a bijection \(\Leftrightarrow m=n\) and rank = n.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(n>m\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(m=n\) and \(A\) is invertible]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(A\) is symmetric]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\mathrm{nullity}(A)=m\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q17 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Rank - Rank of Characteristic Matrix</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>If \(\lambda_0\) is an eigenvalue of \(A\), then \(\mathrm{rank}(A-\lambda_0 I)\):</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) Is less than \(n\) (strictly, i.e., \(\ker(A-\lambda_0 I)\neq\{0\}\))</strong></p><p>Since \(\lambda_0\) is an eigenvalue, there exists \(v\neq0\) with \((A-\lambda_0 I)v=0\), i.e., \(\ker(A-\lambda_0 I)\neq\{0\}\). By rank–nullity, rank\((A-\lambda_0 I)=n-\)nullity\(<n\). This is equivalent to \(\det(A-\lambda_0 I)=0\) (definition of eigenvalue).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Equals \(n\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Equals 0]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Is strictly less than \(n\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Equals \(\lambda_0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q18 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Rank - SVD and Rank</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The rank of a matrix \(A\) in terms of its Singular Value Decomposition \(A=U\Sigma V^T\) equals:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) The number of nonzero singular values</strong></p><p>In the SVD \(A=U\Sigma V^T\), the diagonal entries of \(\Sigma\) are the singular values \(\sigma_1\geq\sigma_2\geq\cdots\geq0\). The rank of \(A\) = the number of nonzero singular values (since \(U\) and \(V\) are orthogonal/unitary and hence invertible, so rank\((A)=\)rank\((\Sigma)\)). The best rank-\(k\) approximation uses the \(k\) largest singular values.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[The number of nonzero singular values]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[The largest singular value]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[The sum of all singular values]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[The smallest singular value]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q19 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Rank - Nullity of Transpose</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>If \(A\) is \(m\times n\) with rank \(r\), then the nullity of \(A^T\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) \(m-r\)</strong></p><p>\(A^T\) is \(n\times m\). rank\((A^T)=\)rank\((A)=r\). By rank–nullity for \(A^T\): nullity\((A^T)=m-\)rank\((A^T)=m-r\). The null space of \(A^T\) is the left null space of \(A\) — vectors orthogonal to all rows of \(A\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(n-r\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(r\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(m-r\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(m+n-r\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q20 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Rank-Nullity - CSIR Style</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(T:\mathbb{R}^4\to\mathbb{R}^4\) be a linear map with \(\ker T^2\neq\ker T\). Which of the following is TRUE?</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(\mathrm{nullity}(T^2)>\mathrm{nullity}(T)\)</strong></p><p>If \(\ker T^2\supsetneq\ker T\) (proper containment), then \(\dim\ker T^2>\dim\ker T\), i.e., nullity\((T^2)>\)nullity\((T)\). This happens when \(T\) has a non-trivial Jordan block — some vectors not in \(\ker T\) get mapped into \(\ker T\) by \(T\), hence land in \(\ker T^2\setminus\ker T\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(T\) is invertible]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\mathrm{nullity}(T^2)>\mathrm{nullity}(T)\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(T^2=0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\ker T=\{0\}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
